So that was my biggest mistake in Scope 3, was sim shipping on so many platforms.

443
00:27:13,205 --> 00:27:18,868
I wish I'd been more focused, specifically in my case, probably on Stadia and PC and Switch.

444
00:27:20,777 --> 00:27:24,802
In any case, that's the story and some of the things I learned along the way of

445
00:27:25,402 --> 00:27:30,087
how I spent two and a half years and forging $20,000 in a puzzle game.

446
00:27:31,569 --> 00:27:34,672
And I'm going to leave you with a couple of closing thoughts, just what went right

447
00:27:34,712 --> 00:27:35,993
and wrong over the entire project.

448
00:27:39,124 --> 00:27:40,886
The way I made this game was iterative.

449
00:27:41,687 --> 00:27:46,394
I made a scope of the game and then when I had the resources and I knew the game

450
00:27:46,434 --> 00:27:48,918
deserved to be a bigger scope, that was when I increased the scope.

451
00:27:49,519 --> 00:27:53,264
I did not sit down and plan to make a massive game and then a

452
00:27:54,626 --> 00:27:55,728
game that I couldn't fund myself.

453
00:27:56,244 --> 00:27:58,346
I find that that's the worst situation to be in.

454
00:27:58,726 --> 00:28:03,070
If you come up with a massive game where you can't personally fund it and you're going

455
00:28:03,131 --> 00:28:08,135
around pitching your small prototype hoping you get funding, you're in a very bad spot.

456
00:28:08,656 --> 00:28:09,917
It's difficult to stay confident.

457
00:28:12,199 --> 00:28:15,282
You're just not in a good negotiating position with whoever needs to give you money.

458
00:28:16,463 --> 00:28:18,425
You're just assuming a lot more risk there.

459
00:28:19,873 --> 00:28:24,756
Personally, the way I work and the way I would recommend working is to design iteratively

460
00:28:24,876 --> 00:28:30,458
and scope up as you know that the game deserves to be a bigger scope and as you can acquire

461
00:28:30,518 --> 00:28:31,699
funding to make that bigger scope.

462
00:28:32,659 --> 00:28:36,101
There's a great deal of confidence that comes with knowing that you have enough money in

463
00:28:36,141 --> 00:28:38,242
the bank account to ship what you're currently working on.

464
00:28:38,402 --> 00:28:39,542
I find that that's really important.

465
00:28:39,862 --> 00:28:43,184
There's been times in my career when I haven't had that and that's maddening.

466
00:28:43,584 --> 00:28:44,705
I would highly recommend against it.

467
00:28:46,245 --> 00:28:50,627
As far as the rest, other things from the game, I'm really happy with how the art worked out.

468
00:28:51,708 --> 00:28:57,250
I don't think the way it was, I wouldn't recommend the way I constructed it, but I'm really happy with how it ended up in the end.

469
00:28:59,111 --> 00:29:02,112
As far as takeaways for Kynem, let's see here...

470
00:29:02,572 --> 00:29:04,533
Yes, I think launching on Stadia was smart.

471
00:29:05,813 --> 00:29:06,593
I'm glad I did that.

472
00:29:06,653 --> 00:29:10,034
There was 22 titles in Stadia when it launched and Kine was one of them.

473
00:29:10,254 --> 00:29:13,134
And that, because there were so few, that gave me a lot of press.

474
00:29:14,354 --> 00:29:18,275
I am really proud that I got to work with Stadia.

475
00:29:18,535 --> 00:29:20,055
Like, that was pretty cool that I pulled that off.

476
00:29:21,296 --> 00:29:24,476
But on the other hand, I wish I didn't launch on all the other platforms.

477
00:29:24,916 --> 00:29:27,957
Launching on so many platforms at the same time just ended up being a lot of work

478
00:29:29,537 --> 00:29:30,757
that I don't think was worth it.

479
00:29:31,953 --> 00:29:38,443
And as far as design goes, I didn't put enough thought into the player experience when the player is stuck on a puzzle.

480
00:29:39,064 --> 00:29:45,474
So this is a point that I don't think really fits into any specific scope, but I really wanted to touch on because it's something important that I missed.

481
00:29:46,567 --> 00:29:50,928
The user experience when a player is stuck in Kine is very bad.

482
00:29:52,068 --> 00:29:54,129
And a large part of this is how the puzzles were structured.

483
00:29:54,149 --> 00:29:56,870
It's the core point of the game, right?

484
00:29:56,890 --> 00:30:00,851
Like Kine is a game that tells a story using puzzles.

485
00:30:01,451 --> 00:30:04,312
And the part of the way I tell that narrative is as soon as you beat a

486
00:30:04,352 --> 00:30:07,993
puzzle, you jump to the next one immediately in a sequence and you see

487
00:30:08,013 --> 00:30:11,354
a little bit of dialogue and then you beat the next puzzle and you jump to

488
00:30:11,394 --> 00:30:12,954
the next one and you see a bit of dialogue.

489
00:30:13,658 --> 00:30:16,845
So, a player is encouraged to continuously play the game.

490
00:30:17,186 --> 00:30:19,652
A player almost never sees the level select screen.

491
00:30:20,634 --> 00:30:22,619
Compare this to an experience like Baba is You.

492
00:30:23,820 --> 00:30:27,342
In this game, you complete a puzzle and you're immediately kicked out to the level select screen.

493
00:30:27,922 --> 00:30:31,684
Every time you beat a puzzle, you're kicked back out to it, and you have a lot of different puzzles to choose from.

494
00:30:31,764 --> 00:30:33,165
It doesn't feel like there's any set order.

495
00:30:34,686 --> 00:30:40,989
In this game, if you're stuck and you back out to the level select screen, that doesn't feel quite as much like failure.

496
00:30:41,909 --> 00:30:43,590
Because you see the level select screen all the time.

497
00:30:44,313 --> 00:30:48,578
in Kine, when you back out to the level select screen, it feels like failure.

498
00:30:49,399 --> 00:30:51,322
It's not something you do unless you're stuck.

499
00:30:52,403 --> 00:30:54,546
And because of that, there's a lot more player friction.

500
00:30:54,586 --> 00:30:55,968
Players generally don't want to do that.

501
00:30:57,583 --> 00:30:58,984
It's just a more negative experience.

502
00:30:59,305 --> 00:31:01,987
And I think in general, what I needed to do is spend more time looking at

503
00:31:02,007 --> 00:31:07,193
players that were struggling, looking at players that did not grok the game

504
00:31:07,233 --> 00:31:09,295
immediately, did not get it as easily.

505
00:31:09,815 --> 00:31:13,439
I think if I was more focused on making sure that those players were still

506
00:31:13,459 --> 00:31:16,162
having fun or I would have caught this earlier on.

